{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17604291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17604291"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:52:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:52:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15819"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15819"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.5,0,0.09,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114650"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8510"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15819"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96653"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8657"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20428"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20448"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114650"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cloaca is a temporary embryological chamber that receives the allantois, hindgut and mesonephric ducts. During the seventh week of development, the urorectal septum divides this chamber into separate passages.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical relationship of the chambers formed by cloacal partitioning?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dorsal urogenital sinus and ventral anal canal","Anterior urogenital sinus and posterior anal canal","Left urogenital sinus and right anal canal","Superior urogenital sinus and inferior anal canal","Medial urogenital sinus and lateral anal canal"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe urorectal septum grows caudally (downward) to divide the cloaca into two chambers. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior urogenital sinus\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior anal canal\u003C/strong\u003E form separate passages for the urogenital and digestive systems respectively. This fundamental embryological process occurs during the seventh week of development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDorsal urogenital sinus and ventral anal canal\u003C/strong\u003E represents the opposite of the correct anterior-posterior arrangement. \u003Cstrong\u003ELeft urogenital sinus and right anal canal\u003C/strong\u003E incorrectly suggests the division occurs in the coronal plane rather than the sagittal plane. \u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior urogenital sinus and inferior anal canal\u003C/strong\u003E incorrectly describes a superior-inferior division when the actual division occurs along the anterior-posterior axis. \u003Cstrong\u003EMedial urogenital sinus and lateral anal canal\u003C/strong\u003E incorrectly suggests a side-to-side arrangement when the chambers are actually arranged front-to-back. This anterior-posterior arrangement established during development persists in the adult anatomy, with the urogenital structures located anterior to the anal canal.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The cloaca divides into the urogenital sinus anteriorly and anal canal posteriorly during week seven of development","The urorectal septum grows caudally to separate the cloaca into distinct urogenital and digestive passages","This embryological division establishes the permanent anatomical relationship between urogenital and digestive systems"],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96653"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15819"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96653"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-18T14:39:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T14:40:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8510"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114650"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relati